    {
        "content": "<p>bjorn3 <a href=\"https://github.com/bytecodealliance/wasmtime/issues/9001#issuecomment-2247197511\">commented</a> on <a href=\"https://github.com/bytecodealliance/wasmtime/issues/9001\">issue #9001</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>You are corrupting the memory of the wasm module by overwriting it's stack and global data, which then results in the wasm module accessing an invalid address. If you want to pass a string to the linear memory, you will have to add a function to allocate memory to the wasm module and then call this function from the host to determine where to write the string.</p>\n</blockquote>",
        "id": 453626581,
        "sender_full_name": "Wasmtime GitHub notifications bot",
        "timestamp": 1721809227
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>FiveMovesAhead <a href=\"https://github.com/bytecodealliance/wasmtime/issues/9001#issuecomment-2247218125\">commented</a> on <a href=\"https://github.com/bytecodealliance/wasmtime/issues/9001\">issue #9001</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>thanks for your reply @bjorn3 ! I see, so I am allocating so much memory that its overflowing into addresses I shouldn't modify.</p>\n<p>Would you be so kind as to give me an example of how to implement the solution that you just described?</p>\n</blockquote>",
